description.en:
*	the origin of cultural heritage and intangible cultural heritage as categories of thought and action, and their development into socio-cultural and economic resources used on the local, national and global levels;
*	contemporary theoretical approaches to cultural heritage and related concepts (including representation, memory, performance, heritagization, narrative, identity, community, migration, transnationalism and diaspora);
*	international organisations (including UNESCO and WIPO) and conventions (UNESCO's Convention Concerning the Protection of the World Cultural and Natural Heritage, and the Convention for the Safeguarding of the Intangible Cultural Heritage) shaping the field of cultural heritage and, more specifically, that of intangible cultural heritage;
*	theoretical approaches in contemporary folkloristics and cultural anthropology that elucidate the specific nature of intangible cultural heritage, processes of heritage making (re- and de-contextualisation), and links between heritage and identity; 
*	case studies from different geographic and socio-cultural contexts explaining the application opportunities of cultural heritage in civil society, the public sector, tourism and other branches of the economy; typical conflicts of interests, and ways of solving them ethically.

objectives.en:
This course aims 
*	to give students factual and theoretical knowledge and vocabulary to describe and analyse processes, participants and relationships pertaining to cultural heritage and, more specifically, intangible cultural heritage on the local, national and international levels;
*	to provide students with an understanding of the specifics of intangible cultural heritage, and its differences from folklore and professional culture;
*	to give students a broad-based understanding of the functions and application opportunities of folklore and cultural heritage in different areas of society, and of common problems and their ethical solutions;
*	to develop students' oral and written communication skills and teamwork skills.

learning_outcomes.en:
Upon passing this course, students should
*	have gained an overview of the history of cultural heritage and intangible cultural heritage, as categories of thought and action, as well as of the main international organisations and conventions guiding developments in the field of cultural heritage on the local, national and international levels;
*	be knowledgeable about the main concepts and approaches in the field of cultural heritage;
*	have a good command of theoretical approaches in contemporary folkloristics and be able to use them to critically analyse relationships between folk culture, professional culture and cultural heritage under global capitalism;
*	have gained a broad-based understanding of the functions and application opportunities of folklore and cultural heritage in individual and collective identity processes, as well as in different areas of society;
*	be capable of identifying diverse actors in the field of cultural heritage (representatives of the state and local governments, communities, entrepreneurs, civil society and cultural elites);
*	have gained an overview of common problems in the field of cultural heritage (including copyright issues), and of ways of preventing and solving them ethically.

independent_work.et:
1) Reading responses and other written or oral assignments based on compulsory readings; to be submitted prior to classroom meetings;
2) participation in recap seminars;
2) oral presentation on the essay topic;
3) a written essay completing the course; deadline TBA.

Guidelines will be given at the beginning and during the course.

grade_preconditions.et:
1) Participation in lectures, seminars (preferably no missed classes!) and online activities;
2) Punctual submission of coursework;
3) Oral presentation;
4) Punctual submission of the final essay.
